% ======================================================================
%  Showcase: Genealogy / rule-based reasoning
%  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  Recommended invocation:
%
%      ./trix --vm-size=2M examples/genealogy.trx              # default family
%      ./trix --vm-size=2M examples/genealogy.trx --grandpa    # the song's cast
%
%  The `--grandpa` flag swaps in the cast of Lonzo & Oscar's 1947
%  song "I'm My Own Grandpa": narrator marries widow, narrator's
%  father subsequently marries widow's daughter, step-relation chain
%  closes into a self-loop.  Section G's classifier announces the
%  punchline -- "jim their own (step-)grandparent! [Lonzo & Oscar
%  1947]" -- by matching a `unify-match` arm whose two name slots
%  share a single `logic-var`, forcing a == b.
%
%  Sections A-F fit in the default 1 MB VM.  Section G's classifier
%  computes `cousins-of` per probe pair, whose nested `flat-map`s
%  briefly push the working set above ~1.2 MB; the per-pair
%  `save`/`restore` reclaims it between pairs.  2 MB gives
%  comfortable headroom for either fact base.
%
%  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  A small "family knowledge engine" that demonstrates Trix's Prolog
%  logic primitives in their natural use cases:
%
%      logic-var / unify / deref / bound?     variables and binding
%      guard / fail                            constraint propagation
%      choice                                  commit-on-first-success disjunction
%      find-all / find-n                       multi-solution collection
%      for-each-solution                       streaming solutions to side effects
%      aggregate                               folding solutions into a scalar
%      copy-term                               rule reuse with fresh variables
%      naf                                     negation-as-failure
%      unify-match                             pattern dispatch on structure
%      once                                    single-shot search
%      def-persist                             cache writes that survive `restore`
%      `(...)#=` / `[...]#=`                   temporary scratch storage
%      `|args|#+N` + local-def                 frame-scoped working state
%
%  Sister showcase: examples/sudoku.trx exercises logic-var / unify /
%  guard / choice on a single dense constraint problem.  This script
%  goes wider -- it covers the rest of the logic surface (recursive
%  rules, multi-solution queries, negation, aggregation, structural
%  pattern dispatch) on a knowledge base that humans recognize at a
%  glance.
%
%  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  The fact base is a four-generation fictional family of 14 people:
%
%    Generation 1     Arthur --- Beatrix
%                          \\___/
%             ___________________|___________________
%            |                                       |
%    Generation 2  Charles --- Helena       Diana --- Ian
%                       \\___/                   \\__/
%                ________|________            ____|____
%               |                 |          |         |
%    Generation 3  Eve --- Kyle  Frank --- Nora  Gareth --- Petra  Heidi
%                  \\__/         \\___/         \\____/
%               ____|____           |              |
%              |         |          |              |
%    Generation 4  Jack  Lily      Mark         Olivia
%
%  --- = spousal pair.   "child of" is straight down through a couple.
%  Heidi is single (used to exercise the "only-child" / "no-spouse" rules).
%
%  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  THE CANONICAL "PREDICATE-AS-ALT-ARRAY" IDIOM
%
%  In Prolog, a fact like `parent(arthur, charles).` and a query like
%  `?- parent(arthur, X).` rely on the engine enumerating fact-base
%  rows and unifying each row against the query.  Trix's `find-all`
%  and `choice` operators take an array of alternative procs and try
%  each in turn, restoring bindings between attempts.  The bridge is
%  this pattern: build, at query time, an array of curry alternatives
%  -- one per fact -- where each curry has the fact baked in via
%  `curry`.  Then hand that array to `find-all` (collect every match)
%  or `choice` (commit on first match).
%
%  Each alt receives its per-call context as a small `[query-vars
%  fact]` array via `curry`'s captured value.  This sidesteps the
%  closure trap that would arise if alts referenced the loop variable
%  by name (`fact` would resolve to the LAST iteration's value when
%  the alts later run, since `def` writes to a shared scope).
%
%  Concretely:
%
%      /parent-alts { |pa ch|#+1
%          parent-facts {
%              /fact exch local-def
%              [pa ch fact] { /ctx exch def
%                             ctx 2 get 0 get  ctx 0 get  unify guard
%                             ctx 2 get 1 get  ctx 1 get  unify guard
%                             ${ [ ctx 0 get deref  ctx 1 get deref ] }
%              } curry
%          } map
%      } def
%
%  Note the proc preamble `|pa ch|#+1` -- a `|...|` locals frame
%  with capacity for 2 named args + 1 working slot (`fact`).  Inside
%  the frame, `local-def` writes to the frame dict; plain `def` walks
%  past frames into userdict and would clobber any caller's same-named
%  binding, so this convention keeps each call's working state
%  isolated and lets predicates recurse safely.
%
%  Each alt unifies the fact's two slots with the query's pa/ch lvars
%  and pushes a single global-VM `${[pa ch]}` pair as the solution
%  result.  find-all collects an Array of pairs; per-direction queries
%  project (`{ 0 get } map` for parent side, `{ 1 get } map` for
%  child side).  Pairs are allocated in the journal-skipped global
%  region so they survive the per-alternative save/restore cycle.
%
%  ======================================================================

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  SECTION 1: Fact base
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%
%  Two relations:
%      parent(P, C)  -- P is a biological parent of C
%      spouse(A, B)  -- A and B are married  (symmetric: stored once)
%
%  Each fact is a 2-element [name name] array.  Names are interned;
%  unification on Names is identity comparison.
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------

% Two fact bases ship with the showcase.  The default models a
% conventional 4-generation tree with no step-relations.  The
% `--grandpa` alternative is the cast of Lonzo & Oscar's 1947 song
% "I'm My Own Grandpa": the narrator marries a widow, his father
% subsequently marries the widow's daughter, and the resulting
% step-relation chain makes the narrator literally his own
% step-grandfather.  Section G's classifier sees this purely from
% the parent / spouse fact base, with no "step" baked into the data.

/default-parent-facts [
    [/arthur /charles] [/beatrix /charles]
    [/arthur /diana]   [/beatrix /diana]
    [/charles /eve]    [/helena /eve]
    [/charles /frank]  [/helena /frank]
    [/diana /gareth]   [/ian /gareth]
    [/diana /heidi]    [/ian /heidi]
    [/eve /jack]       [/kyle /jack]
    [/eve /lily]       [/kyle /lily]
    [/frank /mark]     [/nora /mark]
    [/gareth /olivia]  [/petra /olivia]
] def

/default-spouse-facts [
    [/arthur /beatrix]
    [/charles /helena]
    [/diana /ian]
    [/eve /kyle]
    [/frank /nora]
    [/gareth /petra]
] def

% Lonzo & Oscar (1947) family.  Cast:
%   /jim     -- the narrator ("me")
%   /jane    -- jim's deceased mother (jim's biological mom)
%   /henry   -- jim's father (still living, remarried)
%   /betty   -- the widow jim marries
%   /carl    -- betty's deceased first husband (amy's biological dad)
%   /amy     -- betty's grown daughter, who marries henry
%   /tim     -- jim + betty's son
%   /dan     -- henry + amy's son
%
% Bio parent edges and current spouses only -- deceased spouses (jane,
% carl) appear as parents but not in the spouse facts.  This is enough
% for `step-parents-of` to pick up the comedic chain: betty's daughter
% amy is jim's step-daughter (via betty) AND jim's step-mother (via
% henry), making jim his own step-grandfather through the two-step
% chain jim -> amy -> jim.
/grandpa-parent-facts [
    [/henry /jim]    [/jane /jim]
    [/carl /amy]     [/betty /amy]
    [/jim /tim]      [/betty /tim]
    [/henry /dan]    [/amy /dan]
] def

/grandpa-spouse-facts [
    [/jim /betty]
    [/henry /amy]
] def

% Detect the `--grandpa` flag and bind /parent-facts and /spouse-facts
% to the selected fact base.  `command-line-args` returns the script's
% user-level args (Trix's own --vm-size etc. are consumed before this
% point).
/use-grandpa false def
command-line-args { /arg exch def
    arg (--grandpa) eq { /use-grandpa true store } if
} for-all

/parent-facts use-grandpa { grandpa-parent-facts } { default-parent-facts } if-else def
/spouse-facts use-grandpa { grandpa-spouse-facts } { default-spouse-facts } if-else def

% Everyone we know about (used by some queries).  Derived from facts
% so adding a fact above doesn't desync this list.
/all-people [
    [ parent-facts { 0 get } map  parent-facts { 1 get } map ] flatten
] flatten unique sort def

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  SECTION 2: Predicate alts builders
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%
%  Two alt-array builders -- one per relation.  Both follow the
%  pattern documented in the file header.  Result alts each push
%  TWO scalars: the deref of arg 0, then the deref of arg 1.  This
%  uniform shape lets the same printer/aggregator code drive any
%  relation regardless of which arg was concrete.
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------

/parent-alts { |pa ch|#+1
    parent-facts {
        /fact exch local-def
        [pa ch fact] { /ctx exch def
                       ctx 2 get 0 get  ctx 0 get  unify guard
                       ctx 2 get 1 get  ctx 1 get  unify guard
                       ${ [ ctx 0 get deref  ctx 1 get deref ] }
        } curry
    } map
} def

% spouse is symmetric -- emit both [a b] and [b a] alts so a query
% in either direction works without special-casing the call site.
/spouse-alts { |a b|#+1
    spouse-facts {
        /fact exch local-def
        [a b fact] {
            /ctx exch def
            [
                { ctx 2 get 0 get  ctx 0 get  unify guard
                  ctx 2 get 1 get  ctx 1 get  unify guard
                  ${ [ ctx 0 get deref  ctx 1 get deref ] } }
                { ctx 2 get 1 get  ctx 0 get  unify guard
                  ctx 2 get 0 get  ctx 1 get  unify guard
                  ${ [ ctx 0 get deref  ctx 1 get deref ] } }
            ] choice
        } curry
    } map
} def

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  SECTION 3: Output helpers
%
%  Names print as `arthur` (no leading slash) via `=`.  When we want
%  formatted multi-arg output we use `print-fmt` which accepts Names
%  through {0:O}/{0} interpolation.
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------

% Print a section header.
/heading { |title|#+1
    nl
    (--- ) print title print ( ) print
    /pad 60 title length sub 5 sub local-def
    pad 0 gt { pad { (-) print } repeat } if
    nl
} def

% Print a query line (indented).
/q-print { |msg|
    (    ) print msg =
} def

% Pretty-print a single name (no slash).  `{0}` on a Name in
% print-fmt renders the unprefixed text.
/name-print {
    ({0}) exch mark exch print-fmt pop pop
} def

% Pretty-print a Name array as `[a, b, c]`.
/names-print { |xs|#+2
    xs length 0 eq
    {
        ((none)) print
    }
    {
        /last xs length 1 sub local-def
        0 1 last {
            /i exch local-def
            xs i get name-print
            i last lt { (, ) print } if
        } for
    } if-else
} def

% Pretty-print an array of [x y] Name pairs as `x->y, x->y`.
/pairs-print { |xs|#+2
    xs length 0 eq
    {
        ((none)) print
    }
    {
        /last xs length 1 sub local-def
        0 1 last {
            /i exch local-def
            xs i get 0 get name-print
            (->) print
            xs i get 1 get name-print
            i last lt { (, ) print } if
        } for
    } if-else
} def

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  SECTION 4: Single-solution queries via `once` and `choice`
%
%  `once` runs a goal proc and returns whatever the goal pushes on
%  success, or raises /fail if the goal fails.  Wrapped in `try` to
%  convert failure into a boolean.
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------

% is-parent?(p, c) -- true iff p is a parent of c
/is-parent? { |p c|
    { { p c parent-alts choice  pop  true } once } try
    /fail eq { false } if
} def

% is-spouse?(a, b) -- true iff a and b are married
/is-spouse? { |a b|
    { { a b spouse-alts choice  pop  true } once } try
    /fail eq { false } if
} def

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  SECTION 5: Multi-solution queries via `find-all` / `find-n`
%
%  Each query introduces a fresh logic-var for the unknown slot,
%  builds the alt array via `*-alts`, and uses `find-all` to collect
%  every solution.  Each alt pushes a single global-VM `${[pa ch]}`
%  pair; find-all collects them into an Array of pairs, and the
%  per-direction projection (`{ 0 get } map` for parents, `{ 1 get }
%  map` for children) extracts the side the caller wants.
%
%  Pre-2026-05-10 the alts pushed two scalars and a `keep-side`
%  curry narrowed each alt's push to one of them, because find-all
%  rejected non-persistable composite results.  Now that ${...}
%  composites are accepted (allocated in the journal-skipped global
%  region, transitively restore-safe), the pair-per-alt design is
%  the natural shape -- it hands both names to the open-relation
%  `find-n` / `for-each-solution` queries in the demo without extra
%  wrapping.
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------

% Multi-solution helpers -- each returns an array of Names.
% Note: `*-alts` already returns an array of curries, so we pass it
% directly to `find-all` without an extra `[ ]` wrapper (which would
% nest the alts array inside another array).
/parents-of { |c|#+1
    /p logic-var local-def
    p c parent-alts find-all { 0 get } map
} def

/children-of { |p|#+1
    /c logic-var local-def
    p c parent-alts find-all { 1 get } map
} def

/spouses-of { |a|#+1
    /b logic-var local-def
    a b spouse-alts find-all { 1 get } map unique
} def

% Open query -- BOTH slots unbound -- enumerates the relation itself.
% `find-n` short-circuits: the search stops after n solutions, so the
% remaining facts are never tried (find-all would visit every row).
/first-parent-pairs { |n|#+2
    /p logic-var local-def
    /c logic-var local-def
    n  p c parent-alts  find-n
} def

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  SECTION 6: Compound queries via flat-map composition
%
%  Grandparent / sibling / cousin are all "two parent edges with a
%  shared waypoint".  Each combines two parent-alts into a single
%  alt that succeeds iff both edges hold simultaneously.  flat-map
%  cross-products the parent-fact list with itself.
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------

% grandparent(g, gc) -- exists mid: parent(g, mid) AND parent(mid, gc)
/grandparents-of { |gc|#+4
    /g logic-var local-def
    /mid logic-var local-def
    parent-facts {
        /f1 exch local-def
        parent-facts {
            /f2 exch local-def
            [g mid gc f1 f2] {
                /gctx exch def
                gctx 3 get 0 get  gctx 0 get  unify guard    % f1[0] ~ g
                gctx 3 get 1 get  gctx 1 get  unify guard    % f1[1] ~ mid
                gctx 4 get 0 get  gctx 1 get  unify guard    % f2[0] ~ mid (same!)
                gctx 4 get 1 get  gctx 2 get  unify guard    % f2[1] ~ gc
                gctx 0 get deref
            } curry
        } map
    } flat-map find-all unique
} def

% sibling(a, b) -- exists p: parent(p, a) AND parent(p, b) AND a != b
%
% Note we only ask for ONE shared parent here; full siblings share
% two.  For this tree both parents always co-occur per child, so
% one-shared-parent gives the expected sibling set.
/siblings-of { |target|#+4
    /sib logic-var local-def
    /p logic-var local-def
    parent-facts {
        /f1 exch local-def
        parent-facts {
            /f2 exch local-def
            [target sib p f1 f2] {
                /sctx exch def
                sctx 3 get 0 get  sctx 2 get  unify guard    % f1[0] ~ p
                sctx 3 get 1 get  sctx 0 get  unify guard    % f1[1] ~ target
                sctx 4 get 0 get  sctx 2 get  unify guard    % f2[0] ~ p (same parent)
                sctx 4 get 1 get  sctx 1 get  unify guard    % f2[1] ~ sib
                sctx 1 get deref sctx 0 get deref ne guard   % sib != target
                sctx 1 get deref
            } curry
        } map
    } flat-map find-all unique
} def

% cousin(a, b) -- exists ga, gb, g:
%       parent(ga, a) AND parent(gb, b) AND
%       parent(g, ga) AND parent(g, gb) AND
%       ga != gb AND a != b
% Cousins via composition: cousin(t) = child(sibling(parent(t))).
% Cross-producting four parent-facts arrays directly would be 20^4 ~
% 160K alts -- too many for the demo's VM size.  Composing the three
% smaller queries gives the same answer in a fraction of the work
% and keeps the showcase honest about how Trix tools compose.
/cousins-of { |target|#+4
    /target-parents target parents-of local-def
    /aunts-uncles target-parents { siblings-of } flat-map unique local-def
    /raw-cousins aunts-uncles { children-of } flat-map unique local-def
    /target-sibs target siblings-of local-def
    raw-cousins { |c|
        c target eq not
        target-sibs { c eq } any not
        and
    } filter
} def

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  SECTION 7: Recursive queries -- ancestors / descendants
%
%  Transitive closure of `parent`.  Pure logic-primitive form via
%  recursion + find-all for the multi-solution case.  Each call peels
%  one level of indirection: direct parents are collected, then for
%  each direct parent we recursively gather their ancestors and union
%  the results.
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------

% Use a `|...|` locals frame so the recursive call doesn't clobber
% the outer call's bindings.  Plain `def` writes past `|...|` frames
% into the topmost non-frame dict (userdict), so a recursive call
% would otherwise overwrite the caller's `direct` / `transitive`
% values; `local-def` writes to the frame on top of the dict stack
% and unwinds on return.
/ancestors-of { |target|#+2
    /direct     target parents-of                         local-def
    /transitive direct { ancestors-of } flat-map          local-def
    [ direct transitive ] flatten unique sort
} def

/descendants-of { |target|#+2
    /direct     target children-of                        local-def
    /transitive direct { descendants-of } flat-map        local-def
    [ direct transitive ] flatten unique sort
} def

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  SECTION 7.4: Step-relations (derived from parent + spouse)
%
%  These never fire on the default fact base (everyone has both bio
%  parents married to each other; no step chains).  They light up the
%  `--grandpa` family, which is structured around the step-relations
%  the song depends on.
%
%      step-parent(P, C) :- spouse(P, S), parent(S, C), \+ parent(P, C)
%
%  `step-ancestors-of` is the transitive closure of `step-parents-of`
%  AND biological `parents-of` -- a chain like
%  jim -> amy (step) -> jim (step) is a legitimate step-ancestor walk.
%  The closure has cycles (jim is amy's step-parent and amy is jim's
%  step-parent), so the worker carries a visited-set dict and bails
%  on revisits.
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------

/step-parents-of { |target|#+1
    /candidates target parents-of { spouses-of } flat-map unique local-def
    candidates target parents-of difference
} def

/step-children-of { |target|#+1
    /candidates target spouses-of { children-of } flat-map unique local-def
    candidates target children-of difference
} def

% Cycle-aware transitive closure.  `visited` is a dict allocated by
% the public `step-ancestors-of` wrapper; each name is marked on entry
% and the visited check on top of the proc short-circuits revisits to
% an empty result -- the only way the recursion terminates on the
% grandpa family, which has a jim <-> amy step-parent cycle.
/step-ancestors-of-rec { |target visited|#+4
    visited target known?
    { [] }
    {
        visited begin target true def end
        /direct-bio        target parents-of                                 local-def
        /direct-step       target step-parents-of                            local-def
        /all-direct        [ direct-bio direct-step ] flatten unique         local-def
        /transitive        all-direct {
            /v exch def v visited step-ancestors-of-rec
        } flat-map                                                           local-def
        [ all-direct transitive ] flatten unique sort
    } if-else
} def

/step-ancestors-of { |target|
    target 16 dynamic-dict step-ancestors-of-rec
} def

/step-descendants-of-rec { |target visited|#+4
    visited target known?
    { [] }
    {
        visited begin target true def end
        /direct-bio        target children-of                                local-def
        /direct-step       target step-children-of                           local-def
        /all-direct        [ direct-bio direct-step ] flatten unique         local-def
        /transitive        all-direct {
            /v exch def v visited step-descendants-of-rec
        } flat-map                                                           local-def
        [ all-direct transitive ] flatten unique sort
    } if-else
} def

/step-descendants-of { |target|
    target 16 dynamic-dict step-descendants-of-rec
} def

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  SECTION 7.5: A `def-persist` counter
%
%  Section G wraps each probe pair in `save`/`restore` so the alt
%  arrays / curries `relation-flags` allocates don't pile up.  That
%  also rolls back any plain `def`s done inside the wrapper.  Use
%  `def-persist` to update a scalar counter that escapes the rollback
%  -- a clean, minimal demonstration of the `-persist` family.
%
%  (An earlier version of this file also memoized `ancestors-of` /
%  `cousins-of` etc. into pre-allocated cache dicts.  On a 14-person
%  fact base with 10 probe pairs the per-pair `save`/`restore`
%  already bounds the working set, so the cache cost more in
%  pre-population time and persistent heap than it saved on lookup.
%  Composite-valued caches need their values allocated before the
%  save barrier -- Trix's `def-persist` rejects above-barrier values
%  outright -- so a useful memoization here would also need a richer
%  structure than the workload warrants.  Lesson: `-persist` is for
%  scalar state that must outlive a transactional rollback; reach for
%  it only when that's the actual constraint.)
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------

/calls-made 0 def

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  SECTION 8: Negation-as-failure
%
%  `naf` runs a goal and inverts the result: if the goal fails, naf
%  succeeds (returns true); if the goal succeeds, naf returns false
%  (and rolls back any bindings).
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------

% childless?(p) -- true iff p has no recorded children
/childless? { |p|#+1
    /c logic-var local-def
    { p c parent-alts choice pop } naf
} def

% only-child?(c) -- true iff c has no siblings in the fact base
/only-child? { |c|#+4
    /sib logic-var local-def
    /p   logic-var local-def
    {
        % "exists a sib != c sharing a parent with c"
        parent-facts {
            /f1 exch local-def
            parent-facts {
                /f2 exch local-def
                [c sib p f1 f2] {
                    /octx exch def
                    octx 3 get 0 get  octx 2 get  unify guard
                    octx 3 get 1 get  octx 0 get  unify guard
                    octx 4 get 0 get  octx 2 get  unify guard
                    octx 4 get 1 get  octx 1 get  unify guard
                    octx 1 get deref octx 0 get deref ne guard
                    true
                } curry
            } map
        } flat-map choice pop
    } naf
} def

% unmarried?(p) -- true iff p has no spouse on record
/unmarried? { |p|#+1
    /s logic-var local-def
    { p s spouse-alts choice pop } naf
} def

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  SECTION 9: Aggregation -- counting and folding
%
%  `aggregate` folds over each succeeding alternative with a reducer.
%  Each alt pushes its solution; the reducer consumes it together with
%  the running accumulator and produces the next accumulator value.
%  Same composite-result rules as find-all: scalars or global-VM
%  composites only (the accumulator likewise -- it persists across
%  alts via the running fold).
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------

% count-children(p) -- how many recorded children.  Reducer pops the
% per-alt [pa ch] pair and increments the running scalar count.
/count-children { |p|#+1
    /c logic-var local-def
    0 { pop 1 add } p c parent-alts aggregate
} def

% Total recorded couples-with-children pairs (just `parent-facts length`,
% but expressed via aggregate for the demo).
/total-parent-edges { ||#2
    /a logic-var local-def
    /b logic-var local-def
    0 { pop 1 add } a b parent-alts aggregate
} def

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  SECTION 10: Pattern dispatch via `unify-match`
%
%  Given two people, classify their relationship.  Each arm is a
%  `[pattern body]` pair; unify-match tries each arm's pattern
%  against the input and runs the first body whose unification
%  succeeds.  Within a body, lvars in the pattern are bound to the
%  matching pieces of the input.
%
%  We feed unify-match a `/relation tag` whose payload is a 9-element
%  array: 7 /yes-or-/no flags (parent / child / spouse / sibling /
%  ancestor / descendant / shared-ancestor) followed by the two
%  Names being classified.  Each pattern arm constrains some flag
%  slots and leaves the rest as wildcards (fresh `logic-var`s).
%  First-match wins, so the more specific arms come earlier.
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------

% Helper: convert a boolean to /yes or /no for the unify-match pattern
% language (so each arm reads as a small flag pattern).
/to-yn {
    { /yes } { /no } if-else
} def

% Wildcard: an unbound `logic-var` unifies with anything.  Each call
% produces a FRESH lvar so a single pattern doesn't accidentally
% constrain two slots to be equal.
/_ { logic-var } def

% Helper: does `arr` contain `target`?
/list-contains? { |arr target|
    false
    arr { target eq { pop true } if } for-all
} def

% Build the input tag: 8 /yes-or-/no flags + the two names being
% classified, all wrapped in a /relation tag.  Each call produces a
% fresh array so unify-match's per-arm save/restore can roll back
% bindings cleanly.
/relation-flags { |a b|#+10
    /is-p         a b is-parent?                                 to-yn local-def
    /is-c         b a is-parent?                                 to-yn local-def
    /is-sp        a b is-spouse?                                 to-yn local-def
    /is-sib       a siblings-of b list-contains?                      to-yn local-def
    /is-anc       b ancestors-of a list-contains?                     to-yn local-def
    /is-desc      b descendants-of a list-contains?                   to-yn local-def
    /is-cous      a cousins-of b list-contains?                       to-yn local-def
    /is-shared    a ancestors-of b ancestors-of
                    intersect length 0 gt                        to-yn local-def
    /is-step-anc  b step-ancestors-of a list-contains?                to-yn local-def
    /is-step-desc b step-descendants-of a list-contains?              to-yn local-def
    % This array is consumed immediately by unify-match and never
    % retained, so allocate it as an eq-array (`#=` suffix) in
    % temporary scratch storage rather than persistent heap.
    [ is-p is-c is-sp is-sib is-anc is-desc is-cous is-shared
      is-step-anc is-step-desc a b ]#= /relation tag
} def

% Classify (a, b) by relationship.  unify-match tries each arm in
% order; the first arm whose pattern unifies with the input wins.
% Wildcards are fresh logic-vars (`_`); concrete pattern fields
% (/yes) constrain that slot to /yes.  Order matters: more specific
% relationships (parent, child, spouse) come before fall-through
% (kin, none).
/relation-of { |a b|#+1
    % `self` is a fresh logic-var used in BOTH name slots of the
    % punchline pattern below, so unify-match enforces a == b.  Per
    % call so each invocation gets its own; sharing across calls
    % would let the bound value from one match leak into the next.
    /self logic-var local-def
    a b relation-flags
    [
        [ [/yes _    _    _    _    _    _    _    _    _    _    _] /relation tag  { (parent of) } ]
        [ [_    /yes _    _    _    _    _    _    _    _    _    _] /relation tag  { (child of) } ]
        [ [_    _    /yes _    _    _    _    _    _    _    _    _] /relation tag  { (married to) } ]
        [ [_    _    _    /yes _    _    _    _    _    _    _    _] /relation tag  { (sibling of) } ]
        [ [_    _    _    _    /yes _    _    _    _    _    _    _] /relation tag  { (ancestor of) } ]
        [ [_    _    _    _    _    /yes _    _    _    _    _    _] /relation tag  { (descendant of) } ]
        [ [_    _    _    _    _    _    /yes _    _    _    _    _] /relation tag  { (cousin of) } ]
        % Self-loop punchline: same lvar in slots 10 and 11 forces a == b
        [ [_    _    _    _    _    _    _    _    /yes _    self self] /relation tag
                                                                          { (their own (step-)grandparent! [Lonzo & Oscar 1947]) } ]
        [ [_    _    _    _    _    _    _    _    /yes _    _    _] /relation tag  { (step-ancestor of) } ]
        [ [_    _    _    _    _    _    _    _    _    /yes _    _] /relation tag  { (step-descendant of) } ]
        [ [_    _    _    _    _    _    _    /yes _    _    _    _] /relation tag  { (kin of -- shared ancestor) } ]
        [ _ /relation tag                                                 { (no recorded relation) } ]
    ] unify-match
} def

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------
%  SECTION 11: Demo -- one query of each kind
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------

use-grandpa
{
    (\nGenealogy showcase -- "I'm My Own Grandpa" mode (Lonzo & Oscar, 1947).\n) print
    (Cast: jim (narrator), jane (jim's late mom), henry (jim's dad),\n) print
    (      betty (the widow jim marries), carl (betty's late husband),\n) print
    (      amy (betty's daughter, who marries henry),\n) print
    (      tim (jim+betty's son), dan (henry+amy's son).\n) print
}
{
    (\nGenealogy showcase -- Trix logic primitives over a 14-person family.\n) print
    (See examples/genealogy.trx header for the family-tree diagram.\n) print
    (Pass `--grandpa` for the alternative "I'm My Own Grandpa" cast.\n) print
} if-else

(SECTION A -- single-solution queries (`once` / `choice`)) heading

% Helper: print a query and its yes/no result.
/yn-print { |label b|
    (    ) print label print ( -> ) print
    b { (yes) } { (no) } if-else print nl
} def

use-grandpa
{
    (parent?(henry, jim))        /henry /jim    is-parent? yn-print
    (parent?(henry, dan))        /henry /dan    is-parent? yn-print
    (parent?(jim, amy))          /jim /amy      is-parent? yn-print
    (spouse?(jim, betty))        /jim /betty    is-spouse? yn-print
    (spouse?(henry, amy))        /henry /amy    is-spouse? yn-print
    (spouse?(jim, amy))          /jim /amy      is-spouse? yn-print
}
{
    (parent?(arthur, charles))   /arthur /charles is-parent? yn-print
    (parent?(arthur, eve))       /arthur /eve     is-parent? yn-print
    (parent?(charles, eve))      /charles /eve    is-parent? yn-print
    (spouse?(charles, helena))   /charles /helena is-spouse? yn-print
    (spouse?(helena, charles))   /helena /charles is-spouse? yn-print
    (spouse?(charles, beatrix)) /charles /beatrix is-spouse? yn-print
} if-else

(SECTION B -- multi-solution queries (`find-all` / `find-n` / `for-each-solution`)) heading

use-grandpa
{
    (Children of henry:                   ) print
    /henry children-of names-print nl
    (Children of betty:                   ) print
    /betty children-of names-print nl
    (Parents of jim:                      ) print
    /jim parents-of names-print nl
    (Parents of dan:                      ) print
    /dan parents-of names-print nl
    (Spouses of betty:                    ) print
    /betty spouses-of names-print nl
}
{
    (Children of arthur:                  ) print
    /arthur children-of names-print nl
    (Children of charles:                 ) print
    /charles children-of names-print nl
    (Parents of eve:                      ) print
    /eve parents-of names-print nl
    (Parents of jack:                     ) print
    /jack parents-of names-print nl
    (Spouses of diana:                    ) print
    /diana spouses-of names-print nl
} if-else

% Open queries -- both slots left unbound -- enumerate the relation
% itself, so they read the same for either cast.
(First 3 parent facts (find-n):       ) print
3 first-parent-pairs pairs-print nl

% for-each-solution streams each solution to a side effect (here:
% print) instead of collecting -- the body runs inside the same
% save/restore cycle find-all uses, so only escaping effects (I/O,
% send, stream writes) persist.  With both slots unbound, each
% spouse alt's two-orientation `choice` commits on the stored
% orientation, so every couple streams exactly once.
(Spouse links (for-each-solution):    ) print
/sa logic-var def
/sb logic-var def
{ dup 0 get name-print (~) print 1 get name-print ( ) print }
sa sb spouse-alts for-each-solution
nl

(SECTION C -- compound queries via `flat-map`) heading

use-grandpa
{
    (Grandparents of tim:                 ) print
    /tim grandparents-of names-print nl
    (Grandparents of dan:                 ) print
    /dan grandparents-of names-print nl
    (Siblings of jim:                     ) print
    /jim siblings-of names-print nl
    (Siblings of tim:                     ) print
    /tim siblings-of names-print nl
    (Cousins of jim:                      ) print
    /jim cousins-of names-print nl
    (Cousins of tim:                      ) print
    /tim cousins-of names-print nl
    (\nStep-parents of jim:                 ) print
    /jim step-parents-of names-print nl
    (Step-parents of amy:                 ) print
    /amy step-parents-of names-print nl
    (Step-children of jim:                ) print
    /jim step-children-of names-print nl
}
{
    (Grandparents of jack:                ) print
    /jack grandparents-of names-print nl
    (Grandparents of olivia:              ) print
    /olivia grandparents-of names-print nl
    (Siblings of eve:                     ) print
    /eve siblings-of names-print nl
    (Siblings of mark:                    ) print
    /mark siblings-of names-print nl
    (Cousins of jack:                     ) print
    /jack cousins-of names-print nl
    (Cousins of mark:                     ) print
    /mark cousins-of names-print nl
} if-else

(SECTION D -- recursive transitive closure) heading

use-grandpa
{
    (All ancestors of tim:                ) print
    /tim ancestors-of names-print nl
    (All ancestors of dan:                ) print
    /dan ancestors-of names-print nl
    (All descendants of henry:            ) print
    /henry descendants-of names-print nl
    (All descendants of betty:            ) print
    /betty descendants-of names-print nl
    (\nAll step-ancestors of jim (note the cycle through amy): ) print
    /jim step-ancestors-of names-print nl
    (All step-ancestors of amy:           ) print
    /amy step-ancestors-of names-print nl
}
{
    (All ancestors of jack:               ) print
    /jack ancestors-of names-print nl
    (All ancestors of olivia:             ) print
    /olivia ancestors-of names-print nl
    (All descendants of arthur:           ) print
    /arthur descendants-of names-print nl
    (All descendants of beatrix:          ) print
    /beatrix descendants-of names-print nl
} if-else

(SECTION E -- negation-as-failure (`naf`)) heading

(Who has no recorded children?\n)#= print
all-people {
    /p exch def
    p childless?
    {
        (    ) print p name-print nl
    } if
} for-all

(\nWho is married?\n)#= print
all-people {
    /p exch def
    p unmarried? not
    {
        (    ) print p name-print (    spouses: ) print
        p spouses-of names-print nl
    } if
} for-all

(\nWho is an only child?\n)#= print
% Wrap each iteration in save/restore so the alt arrays / curries
% allocated inside `only-child?` don't pile up across the sweep.
all-people {
    /p exch def
    save /oc-save exch def
    /p-has-parents p parents-of length 0 gt def
    /p-is-only p-has-parents { p only-child? } { false } if-else def
    p-is-only
    {
        (    ) print p name-print nl
    } if
    oc-save restore
} for-all

(SECTION F -- aggregation (`aggregate`)) heading

(Children-count for each parent (via aggregate):\n)#= print
all-people {
    /p exch def
    /n p count-children def
    n 0 gt
    {
        (    ) print p name-print
        (: ) print
        ({0}) mark n print-fmt pop pop
        nl
    } if
} for-all

(\nTotal parent-edges in fact base: )#= print
({0}) mark total-parent-edges print-fmt pop pop
nl

(SECTION G -- pattern dispatch (`unify-match`)) heading

% A handful of pairs to classify.  Grandpa mode swaps in pairs that
% exercise the step-relation arms and the self-loop punchline.
/probe-pairs use-grandpa
{
    [
        [/henry /jim]    [/jim /henry]
        [/jim /betty]    [/jim /dan]
        [/dan /jim]      [/jim /amy]
        [/amy /jim]      [/jim /jim]
        [/tim /dan]      [/dan /tim]
        [/jim /tim]      [/tim /jim]
    ]
}
{
    [
        [/arthur /charles] [/charles /arthur]
        [/charles /helena] [/eve /frank]
        [/jack /mark]      [/arthur /jack]
        [/jack /arthur]    [/jack /heidi]
        [/jack /lily]      [/heidi /jack]
    ]
} if-else def

probe-pairs {
    /pair exch def
    save /pair-save exch def
    (    ) print
    pair 0 get name-print
    ( ) print
    pair 0 get pair 1 get relation-of print
    ( ) print
    pair 1 get name-print
    nl
    % Bump a scalar counter via `def-persist` so the increment
    % survives the per-pair `restore` below.  A plain `def` here
    % would be rolled back, leaving `calls-made` at 0 at the end.
    /calls-made calls-made 1 add def-persist
    pair-save restore
} for-all

(\nrelation-of calls completed (counter `def-persist`ed across pair-saves): )#= print
({0}\n) mark calls-made print-fmt pop pop

(SECTION H -- copy-term: rule reuse with fresh variables) heading

% copy-term takes a term containing logic vars and returns a structurally
% identical term whose variables are FRESH (independent of the originals).
% This is how Prolog's "rule head renaming" works: each call to a rule
% gets fresh copies of the rule-body's variables.
%
% Demonstration: a "skeleton" goal-template containing two lvars.
% copy-term lets us instantiate it twice, with the two instantiations
% being independent.

logic-var /x exch def
logic-var /y exch def
/skeleton [x y] def

(skeleton:                            )#= print
skeleton ==

skeleton copy-term /skel1 exch def
skeleton copy-term /skel2 exch def

(skel1 (fresh copy):                  )#= print
skel1 ==
(skel2 (fresh copy):                  )#= print
skel2 ==

skel1 0 get /alice unify pop
skel1 1 get 42 unify pop

(After binding skel1 to [alice, 42]:\n)#= print
(    skel1: )#= print skel1 ==
(    skel2: )#= print skel2 ==
(    original skeleton: )#= print skeleton ==

(\nDone.\n)#= print
